title: Grateful Dead Live at Shoreline Amphitheatre on 1994-09-18
lineage: Dat (Tascam DA-20) -> Tascam DA-3000 -> Samplitude Professional v11.2.1 -> FLAC/
description:
Set 1

Touch Of Gray-> Greatest Story Ever Told, Jack A Roe, Little Red Rooster, Tennessee Jed, El Paso*, Brown Eyed Women, The Music Never Stopped

Set 2

Iko Iko-> Saint Of Circumstance, Samba In The Rain, So Many Roads-> Samson & Delilah-> Drums-> Space-> The Days Between-> Throwing Stones-> Not Fade Away, E: Brokedown Palace

* Weir on acoustic guitar

reviews.review_text:
Fall '94 Shoreline N3: Twenty-Eights Days Between 28/41: Samson (7:23) -> Drumz (23:16) -> Days Between (13:02) -> Throwing Stones -> NFA. 

Excellent Miller SBD that really amplifies heavy-metal Weir. Sometimes, tbh, it's jarring, especially contrasted with Garcia's softer, acoustic tone. I have in mind, for example, the Jack-A-Roe and - whoa - Rooster, too. It's perhaps in an effort to compensate for a fading Garcia, though he honestly sounds good, here, on the slide.      Otherwise, the Days Between out of space is chilling as always. So Many Roads is also worth the re-listen. Finally, the second set closing NFA is surprisingly energized- and Brokedown Palace encores.

Coming to end, and bittersweet Jerry is slowing here, but some say this is the best So Many Roads ever? I don't think so, but the weariness in Jerry's voice adds a lot to this song (and Day's Between), and it's closing jam is interesting. My favorite So Many Road is 7/9/95, the last show, but that's probably partly sentimental.
